## Job Header Badges ‚Äî Salary Badge Visibility

```html
<span class="job-badge badge-salary is-hidden" id="salaryBadge">
    <i class="fas fa-dollar-sign"></i>
    <span id="salaryRange"></span>
</span>
```

**The salary badge is hidden by default and only shown when there is actual numeric salary data.** Two guards in `renderHeader()`:

1. **Object check**: `salary_range.min || salary_range.max` must be truthy (both `null` and `0` keep badge hidden)
2. **String check**: `salary_range` string must contain at least one digit ‚Äî `/\d/.test(trimmed)` ‚Äî so bare currency symbols (`"$"`, `"USD"`) never show the badge

```javascript
} else if (typeof job.salary_range === 'string') {
    const trimmed = job.salary_range.trim();
    if (trimmed && /\d/.test(trimmed)) salaryDisplay = trimmed;
}
if (salaryDisplay) {
    srEl.textContent = salaryDisplay;
    sbEl.style.display = 'inline-flex';
}
```

### `.job-badge.is-hidden` ‚Äî CSS Specificity Fix
`.job-badge { display: inline-flex }` in the page `<style>` block has the same specificity (one class) as `.is-hidden { display: none }` in `app.css`. Since the page `<style>` loads after the linked CSS, it wins and **all badges are permanently visible** unless overridden.

Fix: add a two-class rule in the page `<style>` block ‚Äî higher specificity (two classes) beats both:
```css
.job-badge.is-hidden {
    display: none;
}
```
**This pattern applies any time a page-level single-class display rule conflicts with `.is-hidden`.** Use `.element-class.is-hidden { display: none }` in the page `<style>` to restore correct hide/show behaviour.

